cs.HC, cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.NE, cs.CY 

The paper deals with assessing driver attention and detecting hazardous events using bio-sensing and vision modalities. This involves analyzing EEG data and facial expressions, which falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The use of deep learning convolution networks for feature extraction and classification suggests that the paper could also fall under computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) categories. The paper also deals with the challenge of limited data availability, which could be relevant to the neural networks (cs.NE) category. Finally, the use of EEG data and vision modalities for driver awareness applications could be relevant to the cybernetics (cs.CY) category.
